Date:  0/0/1941
Source:  NZ Slang
Author:  BAKER
Vol / Page:  38
Edition:
Quote:   the terms to ring a shed and to be a ringer, i.e. to be the fastest and most expert shearer in a shed, have been used for so many generations that they are quite orthodox in the Antipodes.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1951
Source:  Early Canterbury Runs
Author:  ACLAND
Vol / Page:  372
Edition:
Quote:  Jacky Howe.- Sleeveless singlet, cut nearly to the waist under the arms. Named after the famous Jack Howe who rang many of the South Island sheds in the 1890s.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1951
Source:  High Country
Author:  McLEOD
Vol / Page:  29
Edition:
Quote:  The fastest man is called the ringer and there is considerable prestige attached to it, besides the extra profit. Sometimes a man will `ring the shed' in the wethers by sheer courage or brute strength, but when the ewes come in with their softer and less bulky wool, some- one else may come to the fore and displace him.
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1952
